  <h2>Essential Items for Your Kit</h2>
  <p>The contents of an earthquake kit can vary based on season, number of family members, and special health needs. However, some universal supplies belong in every kit:</p>

  <h3>1. Water and Food</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Water:</strong> At least 2–3 liters of drinking water per person per day (small bottles are easier to carry).</li>
    <li><strong>Food:</strong> High-calorie, vitamin-rich, non-perishable items that require no water. Canned goods (with pull-tabs), crackers, energy bars, dried nuts, and dried fruit are ideal.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>2. First Aid and Medical Supplies</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>First Aid Kit:</strong> Bandages, adhesive plasters, antiseptic solution, sterile gauze pads, painkillers, scissors, and tweezers.</li>
    <li><strong>Regular Medications:</strong> Backup supplies of any medications used regularly (heart, blood pressure, asthma, diabetes, etc.) and copies of prescriptions if applicable.</li>
    <li><strong>Hygiene Supplies:</strong> Wet wipes, toilet paper, hand sanitizer, soap, feminine hygiene products, and a toothbrush/toothpaste.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3. Communication, Lighting, and Tools</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Lighting:</strong> Flashlight and headlamp (with spare batteries).</li>
    <li><strong>Radio:</strong> Battery-powered or hand-crank portable radio (may be your only information source during a disaster).</li>
    <li><strong>Whistle:</strong> The most energy-efficient and effective way to signal your location under debris or in the dark.</li>
    <li><strong>Multi-tool Knife:</strong> For various cutting and opening tasks.</li>
    <li><strong>Power Bank:</strong> A fully charged, high-capacity portable charger and compatible cables.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>4. Important Documents</h3>
  <p>Keep photocopies of ID cards, passports, property deeds, mandatory earthquake insurance policies, bank books, and your contact directory in a waterproof folder in the kit. You can also save scanned copies of these documents on a USB drive.</p>

  <h3>5. Clothing and Other Essentials</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Clothing:</strong> Protective, climate-appropriate garments. A rain jacket, thick socks, a beanie, and sturdy-soled hiking shoes.</li>
    <li><strong>Blanket:</strong> Foldable thin thermal (aluminum) blankets (retain up to 90% of body heat).</li>
    <li><strong>Cash:</strong> Some small-denomination banknotes, since electronic payment systems may go down.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Kit Location and Periodic Checks</h2>
  <p>Preparing an earthquake kit is not enough on its own. The kit must be kept in a very easy-to-reach location — for example, in a sturdy cabinet near the front door or right beside your bed. It should be positioned so it does not block your exit route.</p>
  <p>Remember that your kit is a "living kit." Twice a year (for example, at the start of winter and summer), open your kit to check food expiry dates, replace water supplies, test batteries, and update clothing for the season.</p>

